\section{Introduction}

In \cite{RW_P_15}, the present authors develop a theory of chief factors for Polish groups. The development of this theory involves two independently interesting concepts: normal compressions and generalized central products. We here continue these explorations in the setting of \textit{locally compact} Polish (equivalently, second countable) groups. As might be expected, we obtain much stronger results.

We shall use the abbreviations \lcsc for ``locally compact second countable" and \tdlcsc for ``totally disconnected locally compact second countable."
















































\subsection{Normal compressions}

We begin by studying normal compressions. A topological group $H$ is a \textbf{normal compression} of a topological group $G$ if there is a continuous, injective homomorphism $\psi: G \rightarrow H$ with dense normal image. As shown in \cite{RW_P_15}, when $G$ and $H$ are Polish groups, there is a Polish group $\tilde{H}$ so that $\psi$ can be decomposed as a composition $\beta \circ \alpha$ such that $\alpha: G \rightarrow \tilde{H}$ is a closed embedding with normal image and $\beta: \tilde{H} \rightarrow H$ is a quotient map. 



In the locally compact setting, this factorization can be refined to obtain better control over the group $\tilde{H}$.


\begin{thm}[See Theorem~\ref{thm:compression_factoring:tdlcsc}]
Let $G$ and $H$ be \tdlcsc groups with $\psi: G \rightarrow H$ a normal compression map.  Then there is a \tdlcsc group $\tilde{H}$, a closed embedding $\alpha: G \rightarrow \tilde{H}$ with normal image, and a quotient map $\beta: \tilde{H} \rightarrow H$ such that
\begin{enumerate}[(1)]
\item $\psi=\beta \circ \alpha$;
\item $\tilde{H}/\alpha(G)$ is compact;
\item $\ker(\beta)$ is discrete, lies in the FC-center of $\tilde{H}$, and centralizes $\alpha(G)$;
\item $\tilde{H} = {\overline{{\alpha(G)\ker(\beta)}}}$.
\end{enumerate}

\end{thm}

