\subsection{Generalities on locally compact groups}\label{sec:prelim_connected}

\begin{defn}A {\textbf}{covering map} between topological groups $G$ and $H$ is a quotient homomorphism $\psi: G \rightarrow H$ such that there exist identity neighborhoods $U$ in $G$ and $V$ in $H$ such that $\psi$ restricts to a homeomorphism from $U$ to $V$.\end{defn}

Covering maps between \lcsc groups can be characterized as follows: $\psi: G \rightarrow H$ is a covering map if and only if it is a surjective continuous group homomorphism such that the kernel is discrete.

A locally compact group is {\textbf}{almost connected} if the identity component is cocompact. For $G$ a locally compact group, the set of almost connected subgroups is denoted ${\mathcal{U}}(G)$. Note that $G^\circ = U^\circ$ for all open subgroups $U$ of $G$, so ${\mathcal{U}}(G)$ consists precisely of those open subgroups $U$ of $G$ such that $U/G^{\circ}$ is compact.  By van Dantzig's theorem, if $G$ is a \tdlc group, then ${\mathcal{U}}(G)$ is a base of identity neighborhoods.



