A (real) {\textbf}{Lie group} is a topological group that is a finite-dimensional analytic manifold over ${\mathbb{R}}$ such that the group operations are analytic maps. A Lie group $G$ can have any number of connected components in general, but $G^\circ$ is always an \emph{open} subgroup of $G$. 

A Lie group $L$ has a largest connected solvable normal subgroup, the {\textbf}{solvable radical} of $L$; this subgroup is denoted ${\mathrm{Sol}}(L)$.  A connected Lie group with trivial solvable radical is called {\textbf}{semisimple}. Such a group has discrete center, and modulo its center, a semisimple Lie group reduces to a finite direct product of abstractly simple groups.












The manifold structure of a Lie group gives a well-defined dimension $\dim_{{\mathbb{R}}}(G)$, which is additive with respect to extensions. Observe that dimension zero Lie groups are discrete. The dimension places a restriction on directed families of normal subgroups.

\begin{lem}\label{lem:Lie:directed_family}
	Let $G$ be a connected Lie group and let ${\mathcal{{D}}}$ be a directed family of closed normal subgroups of $G$.  Then there exists $N\in {\mathcal{{D}}}$ so that $MN/N$ is discrete in $G/N$ for all $M\in {\mathcal{{D}}}$.
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
	Let $d$ be the maximum of the set $\{\dim_{{\mathbb{R}}}(N) \mid N\in {\mathcal{{D}}}\}$ and take $N\in {\mathcal{{D}}}$ realizing this maximum. For all $M\in {\mathcal{{D}}}$, there is $K\in {\mathcal{{D}}}$ extending $N$ and $M$, since ${\mathcal{{D}}}$ is directed. The group $K/N$ is a dimension zero Lie subgroup of $G/N$, hence $K/N$ is discrete. It follows $MN/N$ is also discrete, verifying the lemma.
\end{proof}








Lastly, Lie groups play a fundamental role in the structure theory of connected groups.

\begin{thm}[Gleason--Yamabe; see {\cite[Theorem 4.6]{MZ}}]\label{thm:yamabe_radical}
	If $G$ is an almost connected locally compact group, then ${\mathop{\rm Rad}_{{{\mathcal{{LE}}}}}\nolimits}(G)$ is compact, and $G/{\mathop{\rm Rad}_{{{\mathcal{{LE}}}}}\nolimits}(G)$ is a Lie group.  

\end{thm}












































































































