A locally compact group $G$ is \textbf{compactly presented} if there is a presentation for $G$ as an abstract group $G= \langle S\mid R \rangle$ so that $S$ has compact image in $G$ and $R$ consists of relators with bounded length. For such groups, we obtain a stronger factorization.

\begin{cor}\label{cor:compression_factoring:compactly_presented}
Let $G$ and $H$ be \lcsc groups with $\psi: G \rightarrow H$ a normal compression map and suppose that $\psi$ restricts to a homeomorphism from $G^\circ$ to $H^\circ$. If $G$ is compactly generated and $H$ is compactly presented, then $\tilde{H}$, $\alpha$, and $\beta$ given by Theorem~\ref{thm:compression_factoring:tdlcsc} can be chosen so that $\tilde{H}/\alpha(G)$ is compact abelian, $\ker(\beta) \le {\mathrm{Z}}(\tilde{H})$, and $\ker(\beta) \simeq {\mathbb{Z}}^n$ for some integer $n \ge 0$.
