\begin{abstract}
We continue the study of normal subgroups and chief factors initiated in \textit{Chief factors in Polish groups}, this time specializing to the case of locally compact groups.  In this context, we obtain tighter restrictions on the factorization of normal compressions. As a consequence, both (non-)amenability and elementary decomposition rank are preserved by normal compressions. We then relate locally compact quasi-products to local direct products. We conclude by studying chief factors in locally compact groups and deriving structure theorems. In particular, we show compactly generated locally compact groups which do not admit `large' chief factors are built from finitely many compact and quasi-discrete groups via group extension. 
\end{abstract}

