\subsection{Quasi-discreteness}




Just as with compact generation, discreteness is not a normal compression invariant, even if we restrict to compressions between non-abelian topologically characteristically simple groups; cf. $\bigoplus_{i\in {\mathbb{Z}}}A_5$ and $\prod_{i\in {\mathbb{Z}}}A_5$. There is a property, however, that is close to discreteness and much better behaved: A \lcsc group $G$ is said to be {\textbf}{quasi-discrete} if $G$ has a dense quasi-center ${\mathrm{QZ}}(G):=\{g\in G\mid {\mathrm{C}}_G(g)\text{ is open}\}$. 

\begin{rmk}
The quasi-center of $G$ is the union of all countable conjugacy classes in $G$, so ${\mathrm{QZ}}(G)$ is the union of all countable normal subgroups of $G$. This gives the following characterization: \textit{For $G$ a \lcsc group, $G$ is quasi-discrete if and only if $G$ contains a countable dense normal subgroup.} The quasi-discrete \lcsc groups are thus exactly the \lcsc groups that arise as normal compressions of countable discrete groups.
\end{rmk}

