\subsection{Existence of local direct models}

It remains to identify which factorizations of locally compact groups admit a local direct model.


Recall that a locally compact group is {\textbf}{almost \tdlc} if the connected component is compact. For these groups, quasi-products are well-behaved.

\begin{lem}\label{lem:quasiproduct:compact}
Let $G$ be a compact group with ${\mathcal{{S}}}$ a generalized central factorization of $G$ and let $I$ be the directed set of finite subsets of ${\mathcal{{S}}}$. For a sequence $(h_N)_{N\in {\mathcal{{S}}}}\in \prod_{N\in {\mathcal{{S}}}}N$ and $J\in I$, set $h_J:=\prod_{N\in J}h_N$ where the product is taken in $G$. If ${\mathcal{{S}}}$ is convergent, then for any sequence $(h_N)_{N\in {\mathcal{{S}}}}\in \prod_{N\in {\mathcal{{S}}}}N$ the associated net $\hat{h}:=(h_J)_{J\in I}$ in $G$ is convergent. 
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
As $G$ is compact, there exists a limit point $k$ of a subnet of $\hat{h}$.  We claim $k$ is indeed the limit point of $\hat{h}$. Given an identity neighborhood $U$ in $G$, there exists $J \in I$ such that $G_{{\mathcal{{S}}} \setminus J} \subseteq U$, since ${\mathcal{{S}}}$ is convergent. Thus, $h_JU = h_{J'}U$ for all $J' \in I$ such that $J \subseteq J'$, and considering $J'$ from our convergent subnet, it follows $h_JU=kU$. It now follows that $\hat{h}$ converges.
\end{proof}



\begin{thm}\label{thm:LDF} 
Let $G$ be an almost \tdlc group. If ${\mathcal{{S}}}$ is a compactly convergent generalized central factorization of $G$, then $(G,{\mathcal{{S}}})$ admits a local direct model.
\end{thm}
\begin{proof} 
Fix $U\in {\mathcal{U}}(G)$ and consider $K:={\overline{\langle {N\cap U\mid N\in {\mathcal{{S}}}} \rangle}}$. The subgroup $K$ is a generalized central product with factorization $\{N\cap U\mid N\in {\mathcal{{S}}}\}$. This factorization is further convergent since ${\mathcal{{S}}}$ is compactly convergent. 

Let $I$ be the directed set consisting of the finite subsets of ${\mathcal{{S}}}$ ordered by inclusion and set $P:=\bigoplus_{N\in {\mathcal{{S}}}}(N,N\cap U)$. An element $h := (h_N)_{N \in {\mathcal{{S}}}}$ of $P$ gives a net $\hat{h}: = (h_J)_{J \in I}$ in $G$ where $h_J:=\prod_{N\in J}h_N$. Since $h$ has only finitely many coordinates that do not lie in $U$, there is a finite $J\subseteq {\mathcal{{S}}}$ so that $h_J^{-1}h_{J'}\in K\leq U$ for all $J'\supseteq J$. The net $(h_J)^{-1}h_{J'}$ for $J'$ extending $J$ is convergent by Lemma~\ref{lem:quasiproduct:compact}, hence the net $\hat{h}$ is convergent. 

We now define $\pi:P\rightarrow G$ via $\pi(h):=\lim \hat{h}$.  It is easily verified that $\pi$ is a continuous homomorphism, that $\pi$ restricts to the identity map on each factor $N$, and that $\pi(P)$ is dense in $G$. 
\end{proof}

