\section{Chief factors and blocks}\label{sec:quasidiscrete}
Associated to any Polish group $G$ is the collection of chief blocks ${\mathfrak{{B}}}_G$, as defined in \cite{RW_P_15}. Each ${\mathfrak{{a}}}\in {\mathfrak{{B}}}_G$ is an equivalence class of non-abelian chief factors under the relation of association. Moreover, the chief blocks appear to be the basic building blocks of compactly generated \lcsc groups, as discovered in \cite{RW_EC_15}.

However, it is not straightforward to interpret the group-theoretic significance of chief blocks, since associated chief factors are not necessarily isomorphic as abstract groups - nor are isomorphic chief factors necessarily associated. In this section we show that the association relation does in fact preserve many group-theoretic properties, so group-theoretic data can be recovered from the chief blocks. 

