	Suppose ${\mathfrak{{a}}}\in {\mathfrak{{B}}}_G$. We say the block ${\mathfrak{{a}}}$ is {\textbf}{connected compact} if some (any) representative is isomorphic to some connected compact group $C$. We say ${\mathfrak{{a}}}$ is \textbf{quasi-discrete} if some (any) representative is quasi-discrete. The block ${\mathfrak{{a}}}$ is {\textbf}{robustly non-negligible} if none of the representatives are compact or quasi-discrete. 
\end{defn}
The previous theorem ensures the definition is sensible. The collection of robustly non-negligible chief blocks is denoted ${\mathfrak{{B}}}_G^r$.

\begin{thm}[See Theorem~\ref{thm:negligible_types}]
Suppose $G$ is a \lcsc group. If ${\mathfrak{{a}}}$ is a chief block of $G$, then ${\mathfrak{{a}}}$ is exactly one of the following: connected compact, quasi-discrete, or robustly non-negligible.
\end{thm}

By the results of \cite{RW_EC_15}, a compactly generated \lcsc group $G$ only has finitely many (robustly) non-negligible chief blocks. We here show the robustly non-negligible chief blocks are responsible for rich large-scale topological structure beyond solvable Lie groups.

\begin{cor}[See Corollary~\ref{cor:negligible_decomp}] 
	Suppose $G$ is a compactly generated \lcsc group. If ${\mathfrak{{B}}}_G^r=\emptyset$, then every essentially chief series $(G_{i})_{i=0}^n$ for $G$ is so that each factor $G_i/G_{i-1}$ is either compact or quasi-discrete.
\end{cor}

The previous corollary implies a compactly generated group $G$ with ${\mathfrak{{B}}}_G^r=\emptyset$ is so that $G^{\circ}$ is compact-by-solvable-by-compact and $G/G^{\circ}$ is elementary with finite rank; see Proposition~\ref{prop:structure_weak}. 

We conclude with an application of our results on chief blocks. A topological group is \textbf{Hopfian} if every continuous self-surjection is also an injection.

\begin{thm}[See Theorem~\ref{thm:Hopfian}]\label{thmintro:Hopfian} 
Let $G$ be a compactly generated \lcsc group. If $G$ has no non-trivial compact or quasi-discrete closed normal subgroup, then $G$ is Hopfian.
\end{thm}




