\begin{prop}\label{prop:block_properties}
	The following are block properties: Being elementary with rank $\alpha$, being amenable, being quasi-discrete, and being isomorphic to a given connected group $H$.
\end{prop}
\begin{proof}
The proofs of the first three are similar, so we only prove that quasi-discreteness is a block property; for the case of elementary groups, one also needs to apply Corollary~\ref{cor:con_association}.

Suppose $G$ is an \lcsc group and ${\mathfrak{{a}}}\in {\mathfrak{{B}}}_G$ is so that there is a quasi-discrete $K/L\in {\mathfrak{{a}}}$. Take $A/B$ another representative and form the uppermost representative $M/C\in{\mathfrak{{a}}}$ as given by Proposition~\ref{prop:upper-rep}.

The factor $M/C$ is a normal compression of $K/L$, and these chief factors are topologically perfect. Corollary~\ref{cor:compression:quasidiscrete} thus ensures that $M/C$ is quasi-discrete. On the other hand, $M/C$ is also a normal compression of $A/B$. Applying again Corollary~\ref{cor:compression:quasidiscrete}, we deduce that $A/B$ is quasi-discrete, so all representatives are quasi-discrete.

For the last property, suppose $K/L\in {\mathfrak{{a}}}$ is isomorphic to a connected group $H$ and let $M/C$ be the uppermost representative. The block $M/C$ is connected via Corollary~\ref{cor:con_association}, so  Corollary~\ref{cor:Zerling:perfect} ensures that $K/L$ is isomorphic to $M/C$. Consider $A/B$ a second representative. There is again a normal compression map $A/B\rightarrow M/C$. The block $A/B$ is connected via Corollary~\ref{cor:con_association}.  Corollary~\ref{cor:Zerling:perfect} then ensures that $A/B$ is isomorphic to $M/C$. All representatives of ${\mathfrak{{a}}}$ are therefore isomorphic to the connected group $H$.
\end{proof}

