\end{cor}
\begin{proof}
Let ${\{1\}}=G_0<\dots <G_n=G$ be an essentially chief series for $G$, so each factor $G_i/G_{i-1}$ is either compact, discrete, or chief.  Discrete factors and abelian chief factors are obviously quasi-discrete.  Theorem~\ref{thm:negligible_types} then implies that every non-abelian chief factor in the series is either compact-connected or quasi-discrete, and the result follows.
\end{proof}


