\subsection{Application: Hopfian property}
A group is called \textbf{Hopfian} if every self-surjection is also an injection. Using the machinery of chief blocks, we show many compactly generated \lcsc groups are Hopfian. Our analysis of the Hopfian property is via the notion of block morphisms developed in \cite{RW_P_15}; we direct the reader to loc. cit. for details on this construction. 

By \cite[Proposition~8.5 and Theorem~8.8]{RW_P_15}, a continuous epimorphism $\phi:G\rightarrow H$ of Polish groups induces a canonical strong block monomorphism $\psi:(X_H,{\mathfrak{{B}}}_H)\rightarrow (X_G,{\mathfrak{{B}}}_G)$. On the level of chief factors, this map sends $A/B$ to $\phi^{-1}(A)/\phi^{-1}(B)$. It turns out this is well-defined on blocks and preserves the partial order.


\begin{lem}\label{lem:robust_injection}
Suppose $G$ and $H$ are \lcsc groups and $\phi:G\rightarrow H$ is a continuous surjection. Then the canonical strong block monomorphism $\psi:(X_H,{\mathfrak{{B}}}_H)\rightarrow (X_G,{\mathfrak{{B}}}_G)$ induced by $\phi$ is such that $\tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{B}}}_H^r) =  {\mathfrak{{B}}}_G^r \cap \tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{B}}}_H)$.
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
Take ${\mathfrak{{a}}}\in {\mathfrak{{B}}}_H$ and suppose $\tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{a}}})\notin{\mathfrak{{B}}}_G^r$. Taking $A/B\in {\mathfrak{{a}}}$, that $\psi$ is a strong block monomorphism implies that $A/B\simeq \psi(A/B)$ and that $\psi(A/B)\in \tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{a}}})$.  The block $\tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{a}}})$ is not robustly non-negligible, so Theorem~\ref{thm:negligible_types} implies $\tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{a}}})$ is either connected compact or quasi-discrete. The factor $\psi(A/B)$ is thus either a compact connected group or a quasi-discrete group. The factor $A/B$ is then either a compact connected group or a quasi-discrete group. Hence, ${\mathfrak{{a}}}$ is either compact connected or quasi-discrete. That is to say, not robustly non-negligible.  This demonstrates that $\tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{B}}}_H^r) \subseteq  {\mathfrak{{B}}}_G^r \cap \tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{B}}}_H)$.

Conversely, suppose ${\mathfrak{{a}}} \not\in {\mathfrak{{B}}}_H^r$.  We may find $A/B \in {\mathfrak{{a}}}$ which is either compact or quasi-discrete.  If $A/B$ is compact or quasi-discrete, then so is $\psi(A/B)$, since $\psi$ is a strong block monomorphism. The block $\tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{a}}})$ is thus not robustly non-negligible.  This demonstrates that $\tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{B}}}_H \setminus {\mathfrak{{B}}}_H^r) \subseteq  {\mathfrak{{B}}}_G \setminus {\mathfrak{{B}}}_G^r$, and hence $\tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{B}}}_H^r) = {\mathfrak{{B}}}_G^r \cap \tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{B}}}_H)$.
\end{proof}

We stress that it is important to consider \emph{robustly non-negligible blocks} for the previous lemma. Indeed, negligible blocks can become non-negligible in a quotient, so in general we do not have $\tilde{\psi}({\mathfrak{{B}}}_H^*) \subseteq {\mathfrak{{B}}}_G^*$, where ${\mathfrak{{B}}}_G^*$ is the set of non-negligible blocks.



















